  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best poems on women you have come across?",
  "response": "There are countless poems that celebrate, explore, and honor women in all their complexity. Here are some of the most cherished and powerful poems about women, written by poets from diverse backgrounds and perspectives:\n\n### **Classic Poems**\n1. **\"Phenomenal Woman\" by Maya Angelou**  \n   A celebration of women\u2019s inner strength, beauty, and confidence. Angelou\u2019s empowering voice resonates deeply with readers.\n\n2. **\"She Walks in Beauty\" by Lord Byron**  \n   A romantic ode to a woman\u2019s grace and elegance, capturing her physical charm and inner radiance.\n\n3. **\"A Woman\u2019s Last Word\" by Robert Browning**  \n   A reflective and tender poem that delves into the complexities of love, relationships, and a woman\u2019s voice.\n\n4. **\"To the Ladies\" by Lady Mary Chudleigh**  \n   An early feminist poem challenging societal expectations of women and advocating for their independence.\n\n5. **\"Goblin Market\" by Christina Rossetti**  \n   A narrative poem exploring themes of sisterhood, temptation, and women\u2019s resilience.\n\n---\n\n### **Modern and Contemporary Poems**\n6. **\"Wild Geese\" by Mary Oliver**  \n   A poem that speaks to the freedom and strength of women, encouraging them to embrace their true selves.\n\n7. **\"The Woman Who Walked into Doors\" by Paula Meehan**  \n   A poignant exploration of a woman\u2019s struggles and survival in the face of adversity.\n\n8. **\"Still I Rise\" by Maya Angelou**  \n   Another iconic Angelou poem, celebrating the unbreakable spirit of women in the face of oppression.\n\n9. **\"The Moon and the Yew Tree\" by Sylvia Plath**  \n   A haunting and introspective poem that reflects on femininity, motherhood, and identity.\n\n10. **\"For My Daughter\" by Wanda Coleman**  \n    A deeply moving poem that speaks to the challenges and hopes of raising a daughter in a complex world.\n\n---\n\n### **Poems About Women\u2019s Strength and Resilience**\n11. **\"The Mother\" by Gwendolyn Brooks**  \n    A powerful and heartbreaking exploration of motherhood and the sacrifices women make.\n\n12. **\"Woman Work\" by Maya Angelou**  \n    A tribute to the tireless labor and strength of women, often unnoticed and unappreciated.\n\n13. **\"The Woman I Am in My Dreams\" by Maxine Tynes**  \n    A celebration of the inner strength and identity of women.\n\n---\n\n### **Poems Celebrating Women\u2019s Voices**\n14. **\"A Litany for Survival\" by Audre Lorde**  \n    A powerful call to action and self-affirmation for women, particularly women of color.\n\n15. **\"Poem to My Sister\" by Eavan Boland**  \n    A meditation on the shared experiences and bonds between women.\n\n16. **\"For the Young Who Want To\" by Marge Piercy**  \n    A motivational poem encouraging women to pursue their passions and dreams.\n\n---\n\n### **Poems from Non-Western Perspectives**\n17. **\"Her Words\" by Faiz Ahmed Faiz**  \n    A beautiful Urdu poem celebrating the power and beauty of a woman\u2019s voice.\n\n18. **\"The Language of the Universe\" by Nayyirah Waheed**  \n    A contemporary poem that speaks to the depth and resilience of women.\n\n19. **\"I Celebrate Myself\" by Kamla Das (from *The Dance of the Eunuch*)**  \n    A bold and unapologetic exploration of female identity and desire.\n\n---\n\nThese poems offer a wide range of perspectives on womanhood, from empowerment and beauty to struggle and resilience. Each one is a testament to the enduring strength and complexity of women throughout history and across cultures. Let me know if you'd like to explore any of these in more detail!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
